description: Join us for the 2025 Blanche, Edith, and Irving Laurie Chair in Women’s Studies Symposium, ACTION NOW: Feminist Climate Leadership for a World in Crisis.   Women and gender-diverse leaders are driving transformative climate solutions. This symposium convenes climate scientists, activists, scholars, policymakers, and artists for a powerful day of programming on the critical need for feminist leadership in climate action. Through engaging discussions, we’ll examine the intersections of gender, migration, environmental justice, and scientific innovation—showcasing the strength of community-driven solutions in confronting the climate crisis.    Seating is limited—register today to secure your spot.    Presented by the Institute for Women's Leadership Consortium in collaboration with Douglass Residential College, School of Environmental and Biological Sciences, Rutgers Global, and the Rutgers Climate and Energy Institute.

description: Join us for an engaging hybrid event tailored specifically for graduate students!  Learn firsthand about the ins-and-outs of publishing academic papers from the experienced perspective of Naomi Shin, Associate Editor at Studies in Hispanic and Lusophone Linguistics. Dr.Shin will guide you through the essential steps involved, share valuable strategies, and provide practical advice to help you successfully navigate your own publishing journey.   Guest Speaker: Naomi Shin University of New Mexico Naomi's primary interests include child language acquisition, bilingualism, language contact, and sociolinguistics. Her research focuses on patterns of morphosyntactic variation, examining how these patterns are acquired during childhood and how they change in situations of language contact. She co-directs the Lobo Language Acquisition Lab.   Join Zoom Meetinghttps://rutgers.zoom.us/j/91738606098?pwd=95MDci3sgu6JxeozR9Hei2AqPOf9V6.1 Meeting ID: 917 3860 6098Password: 515418
name: Demystifying Academic Publishing: A Guide for Graduate Students

description: The annual Rites of Passage Ceremony is a pre-commencement celebration to honor Black and Latinx/e-identified students who through resolute persistence have successfully completed an undergraduate or graduate degree at Rutgers University—New Brunswick. The event recognizes their accomplishments, hard work, and dedication, while simultaneously acknowledging the accomplishments of our student’s families and networks of support. Distinguished speakers, student awards, performances, and the incorporation of African culture and traditions—specifically the culminating Kente Stole presentation—all add to the vibrancy of this celebratory day. Participation in the Rites of Passage Ceremony is open to all Black and Latinx-identified Rutgers University–New Brunswick Undergraduate and Graduate students who have earned their degrees between January 2025 and August 2025. To participate, students must register by Friday, May 2nd, 2025 through the getINVOLVED portal. Only students registered by the deadline will be guaranteed Rites of Passage graduate perks! The late registration deadline is May 14th (Day of ceremony). All graduates are required to wear their academic regalia, which can be purchased from the Barnes and Noble Rutgers University Bookstore on Somerset Street. There is no cost to participate in Rites of Passage for graduates or guests. All graduates who register will receive the following:-1 Free Kente Cloth Stole-7 guest tickets-Access to reception  If you have specific questions about your registration or the ceremony, please email rop@echo.rutgers.edu. Please note that all graduates need to be checked-in between 2:30-3:30pm. The graduation will start promptly at 4:00pm.  Visit the Rites of Passage website for more information!
name: 33rd Annual Rites of Passage Ceremony Registration
organizationNames: Center for Latino Arts and Culture
Paul Robeson Cultural Center
Rites of Passage Ceremony
